<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<!--
  UI Macro: kb_intel_suggestion_panel
  Application: GLOBAL  (recommended) — but works in any scope because there is
                                       no `current` reference, no GlideRecord.

  REPLACES the old Jelly-evaluate macro that broke across scopes.

  This macro is now intentionally DUMB — it just renders an empty placeholder
  div with id="kbi_panel". The Client Script "KB Intel — Load Suggestions"
  (CS_incident_suggestions_load.js) finds the div by id, calls the
  SuggestionAjax Script Include via GlideAjax, and fills it with HTML.

  Why this works where the old approach failed:
    - No <g:evaluate> block → no Jelly server-side evaluation needed
    - No `current` reference → no cross-scope binding issues
    - No GlideRecord call from Jelly → no scope-related access failures
    - The Client Script reads g_form.getUniqueValue() which is reliable in
      any scope, and GlideAjax is the official cross-scope contract.

  Steps to install:
    1. (Optional) Switch application picker to GLOBAL — for safety, since the
       formatter renders on a Global table. Works in scoped app too if you
       prefer to keep it in KB Intelligence.
    2. System UI → UI Macros → New
       Name: kb_intel_suggestion_panel
       Active: true
       XML: paste the entire <j:jelly> block below
    3. System UI → Formatters → New
       Name: KB Intelligence Suggestions
       Table: incident
       Formatter: kb_intel_suggestion_panel
    4. Configure form layout for incident → add the formatter near the top.

  If the formatter is missing from the form layout, the Client Script will
  create the panel dynamically and inject it above the form fields — so this
  macro is technically optional. Use it for explicit placement control.
-->
<j:jelly trim="false" xmlns:j="jelly:core" xmlns:g="glide">
  <div id="kbi_panel" style="border:1px solid #d0d7de;padding:12px;border-radius:6px;background:#f6f8fa;margin:10px 0;">
    <em style="color:#57606a;">Loading similar past resolutions…</em>
  </div>
</j:jelly>
